{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00393342158/1945081601/0306.xml":{"full_text":"ALL MANPOWER\nCONTROLS ARE\nLIFTED TODAY\nFree Labor Market De\ntermines Hiring\nFrom Now On\nOutlining post V-J Day activities\nof the War Manpower Commission,\nfollowing elimination of rigid war\ntime manpower controls. F. W. Hun\nter Regional Director of the WMC\nparticular emphasis on industries\nwhich may become reconversion\nbottlenecks and thus delay mass\nre-employment throughout the coun\ntry as a whole.\n4\u2014The full facilities of t.h\u00ab Unit\ned States Employment Service will\nagain be made available to all em\nployers, including those for whom\nservices were restricted because of\nwar requirements.\n5 Expanded services will be ren\ndered to veterans to assist them in\ntheir re-adjustments to civilian em\nployment.\n6\u2014Increased emphasis will be giv\nen to job counseling and other per\nsonalized services, to assist b\nseekers to adapt their wartime ex- j\nperiencc to peacetime job opportuni-1\nties.\ners; expansion of the counseling\nservices to veterans and other seek\ners who need such assistance; mak\ning available to all employers, labor\norganizations and community groups,\nconcerned with production and em\nployment planning, current infor\nmation concerning the present and\nprospective labor market situation\nin the area and in other areas, as\nnecessary; provision of technical\nservices to all individuals and or\nganizations dealing with employ\nment counseling or the hiring and\nplacing of workers, to the end that\ninformation and techniques avail\nable to the Employment Service may j\nhave the widest possible use in im\nproving counseling and placement\nactivities, wherever performed.\u201d\nCOUNSELOR FOR\nSE INDIANS HAY\nPROTEST RULING\nHaas Says Petitioners Not\nSatisfied with Ickes'\nDecision\nDeclaring that, as counsel for the\npetitioners, he is \"not at all satis\nlied\u2019\u2019 with the order of Secretary\nof the Interior Harold Ickes, setting\naside Indian reservations in South\ntoday announced the adoption of a\nnational seven-point reconversion\nprogram by the Manpower Commis\nsion. This program is to be put into\neffect immediately through the\nCommission's 1,500 local U. S. Em\nployment offices throughout the\ncountry and in Alaska.\nThe reconversion program pro\nvides for stimulating reconversion\nactivities and the speedy rc-employ\nmrnt of displaced workers, at the\nsame time restoring a free labor\nmarket, Mr. Hunter declared. The\nprogram includes:\nControls Lifted\n1 All manpower controls are to\nbe lifted immediately and in their\nplace cooperative community action\nto speed reconversion will be In\nitiated.\n2\u2014 The number and type of avail\nable workers, including returning\nveterans, and the immediate and\nprospective job opportunities in each\ncommunity will be determined in\ncooperation with local management,\nlabor and civic groups and action\nwill be taken by the WMC and local\nUSES offices in cooperation with\nth\u201d communities, to speed recon\nversion and re-employment.\n3- Maximum assistance will be\nprovided to workers and employers\nin manning civilian industries, with\nAid Workers\n7 Displaced war workers, many\nof whom have migrated during ihe\nwar, will Ire assisted in finding em\nployment in other communities\nwhere civilian production has ex\npanded. USES offices will give pre\nferential treatment to all recon\nversion activities. Local surveys of\nemployers' needs, which have been\nlimited to war industries in the\npast, will be re-directed to civilian\nindustries in every community and\ntim blueprint c-C community job\navailability thus obtained will be\nfurnished local leaders. Tiie WMC\nsaid efforts will then be made to see\nthat essential civilian industries,\nand industries important to the\nnational reconversion program as a\nwhole, are fully manned.\nThis community employment plan\nning will be based entirely on vol\nuntary activity, in order to speed\nreconversion and to assure maxi\nmum future employment. Field in\nstruction issued to regional man\npower directors call for immediate\nsteps to be taken to provide the\nfollowing services:\nPreferential Service\n\"Preferential service to civilian\nactivities of key importance to re\nconversion nationally and locally:\n1 extension of services to all employ\nSchilling\nGarlic Salt\nReal garlic favor\nthis easy way\nONLY BRIEF MEET\nSET FOR REGULAR\nCOUNCIL SESSION\nStill enmeshed in the ramifica\ntions of equalizing the city's as\nsessment rolls, the Juneau Common\nCouncil tomorrow evening will con\nfine its regular semi-monthly busi\nness meeting to a few items of\nminor but pressing nature, it was\nannounced today by Mayor Ernest\nParsons.\nWith the brief session out of the\nway, the council will then turn its\nattention back to taxes. A special\ncouncil meet is to be called the\nfirst part of next week\u2014at which;\ntime the tax mill rate is to be set.\nMayor Parsons and Council Fin\nance Committeeman Don Skuse to\nday pointed out an error in in-;\nterpretation of the City Budget\nadopted at the recent special coun\ncil meeting. Publicity concerning\nthe budget, they said, conveyed the\nimpression that short term bank\nborrowings made to carry the\npresent administration until tax\nrevenues roll in\u2014now totalling $70,\n000\u2014would not be repaid from\nthis year's revenues.\nThat is not an exact picture of\nthe matter, they said. The current\nborrowings will be repaid as soon\nas tax moneys are available. How\never, the new budget will not pro\nvide\u2014as Mayor Parsons had con\ntemplated\u2014for a $60,000 reserve\nwhich would have enabled the next\nadministration to carry through\ni without making new loans. The\ni present council did not feel that\nI it could assume that full load,\nSkuse said.\nDETROIT ALMOST HIT\nBY JAPANESE BALLOON\nDETROIT. Aug 16.\u2014State civilian\ndefense authorities today disclosed\nthat the heavily industralized De\nI troit area was almost hit by a Japa\nI ncse balloon bomb last May.\ncast Alaska, Theodore Haas, Chief\nCounsel for the Alaska Native Ser\ni vice, is now in Juneau engaged in\na study of the Ickes opinion.\nMr. Haas is working here in con\njunction with George Folta, Interior\nDepartment Counsel at Large. From\ntheir study of the opinion it will be j\ndetermined whether a motion for\u2018\n1 re-hearing will be entered on behalf I\nof the petitioning Indian commun-1\nitiss of Hake, Hydaburg and Kla-1\nwoek, Mr. Haas said here today.\nSalmon packers also have express\ned dissatisfaction with the Ickes de-\ncisicn. through their spokesman, W. j\nC. Arnold. Both sides have already\nasked for extension of the time for I\nfiling requests for re-hearing, Mr. I\nHaas said, and Secretary Ickes has\ngranted extension until August 31.\nBoth petitioners and protestants had,\nasked for extension until Septem\nber 30.\nI\nI\nHOLIDAY QUIET\nREIGNING HERE\ni\n\nOnly sporadic activity, in spots, I\ngave indication today that Gas-1\ntineau Channel was paying any at\ntention to business on this day\nlocally proclaimed for commemora\ntion of the downfall of Japan.\nJuneau Lumber Mills, Juneau Cold\nI Storage, Goldstein Building, restau\ni rant, bar and hotel workers are on\ntheir jobs but they are almost\nalone in their labors. In Federal\nand Territorial offices, only a few I\nsolitary workers are holding out in\n1 isolated endeavor.\nThe Juneau Chamber of Com-\nmerce was to hold its regular meet-\ning this noon. Nearly everyone else I\nis enjoying a holiday. i\nA SHOT OF OIL i\nNEW YORK An extra drop of\noil the size of a pin-head can spoil i\nthe efficiency of a $12,000 torpedo,!\naccording to Carl G. Prsis, general j\nmanager of the American Can Com-1\npany\u2019s Amertorp plants. The course\ncf the torpedo is directed by gyro-'\nsccpes. so delicately adjusted they\nare oiled with hypodermic needles.\nGEORGE BROTHERS\nSuper Market\nPhones 92-95\u20142 Free Deliveries Daily\nGEORGE BROTHERS\nLiquor Store\nOpen io 12 Midnight\nCalvert Special, 5th, S4.20\nCalvert Reserve, 5th, $4.65\nLord Calvert, 5th $5.25\nCome In and Ask for Your\nFR\nCalvert\nKEY CHAIM\nAVAILABLE IN GROCERY OR LIQUOR\nDEPARTMENTS\nThursday Friday and Saturday\nWHILE THEY LAST!\nJust the Thiny for\nThose Extra Keys\nThe Best Cash Grocery in Juneau\nBURMA JAP\nSURRENDER\ni PLAN MADE\n75,000 Allied Prisoners\nBelieved to Be in\nSingapore\nRANGOON. Aug. 16\u2014Southeast\nAsia command headquarters was\nmaking arrangement today to accept\nthe local surrenders of Japanese\ncommanders of Burma, Thailand,\nMalaya and the Netherlands East\nIndies.\nOne of the surrender conditions,\nit was understood here, calls on the\nJapanese commanders to hand over\nthe installations intact or face the\nfiring squad.\nSurrenders of Burma and Thailand\nwill be accepted at Rangoon, JJurma\ncapital, and the Malayan and In\ndies surrenders will be handled at\nSingapore.\nThe most immediate problem is\nthe handling of Allied prisoners, of\nwhom 75,000 are believed to be on\nSingapore island. Medical person\nr.oil and medicines are expected to\nbe parachuted to them and Red\ndress and other agencies will follow\nan hospital ships and transports as\nfast as they can be assembled.\nThe number of Japanese remaining\nn the southeast Asia command thea\n:re since depletions of the Sumatra\nind Java garrisons is estimated at\nbetween 800,000 and 900,000.\nJap Balloons\nStill Threat\nSEATTLE, Aug. 16\u2014The wind\nwafted, bomb carrying balloons\nJapan sent to America in a spirit\nof wartime giving may keep search\ning parties busy after the last shot\nis fired in the Pacific, authorities\nsaid today, observing the word of\npeace may be slow to reach Nip\npon's soldiers but can never reach\nthese paper missionaries of death.\nThe problem now, they said, is\nto prevent injury or damage from\nbombs still undiscovered.\nUnder consideration is a plan to\nsend search parties to the scene\nof each bomb and have them work\nback over the assumed bomb route,\naided by meterological data on pre\nvailing winds.\nApproximately 230 were found\nduring the wrar, scattered from Al\naska to Mexico. How many might\nhave fallen unnoticed, their bombs\nunexploded, cannot be guessed.\nA flight of hundreds was sighted\noff the Aleutians during the San\nFrancisco United Nations Con\nference, but not one was known to\nhave reached shore.\nALIBI\ni GREEN BAY, Wise.,\u2014Sgt. Norbert\nRasmussen's excuse to Police for not\nj being able to produce his driver's\ni license was a new one to the law.\nRasmussen, who had been a pris\noner of war in Germany, casually\nexplained that in an attempt to\nconceal his identity he had eaten\nhis 'license when captured last De\ncember.\ni EASY WINNER\nCHICAGO Attorney Nicholas\nCaruso, representing Mrs. Cather\nine Lowe. 21, in her suit for divorce\nfrom her husband, William, 29, a\njockey, told Superior Judge John A,\nSbarbaro:\n\u201cI don't know whether your honor\nis acquainted with race track phrase\nology, but Mrs. Lowe was left at\nthe post.\u201d\nWell, she's an odds-on favorite tc\nj win this race,\u201d Judge Sbarbaro ob\nserved as he signed the divorce de\ncree.\nAUTOCRAP H Fleet Ad\nmiral C. W. Nlmiti, commander\nIn-chief of Pacific Ocean Areas,\nsigns a \u201cshort snorter\" on Guam.\nYES WE HAVE LOTS OF CUBE SUGAR\nJVo Strings Attached\nAND_\nLimited amounts of Rath's Breakfast Pork Sausage in cans, Hershey\nand Nestle's Milk Chocolate, Corned Beef Hash, Potato Chips, Jello,\nI Assorted Pickles\nALSO....\nPlenty oi FRESH FRUITS and VEGETABLES including the following\nBananas, Peaches, Grapes, Plums, Pears, Apples, Cantalopes, Casa\nbas, Honeydews, Avocados, Corn-on-Cob, Bunch Beets, Cucumbers,\nEgg Plant, Danish Squash, Celery, Lettuce, Tomatoes, Cabbage,\nGreen Peppers and others.\nCome In and See or Call 10 or 24\nPhone\n767\nPhone\n767\nFRIDAY-SATFRDAY\n2\n1\nBAKER\u2019S Unsweetened 8 ea.\nCHOCOLATE ALL FOR\nCAKE FLOCK\nSOFT-AS-SILK\n2\n2\n2\